			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">In EQ 1, outside of LdoN’s, “adds” usually indicated sloppy pulling or a mistake on someone’s part. Monk’s and SK’s surgically separated mobs to pull only 1 back to the group. Pulling at that level was an art form.
<br />

<br />
Soloing using kiting skills, whether traditionally druid kiting or hate/aggro kiting was also an art form and you could see extremely skillful players quad kiting dangerous mobs around a zone. Kiting at that level was an art form. 
<br />

<br />
In EQ2 pulling has been reduced from the art form it used to be to a function anyone can do. Adds are a normal part of adventuring in EQ2, whether the mob is solo or a group mob. Kiting has been nearly completely eliminated with EQ2’s philosophy, “if you can damage a mob, it can damage you.” 
<br />

<br />
Combat now has Heroic Moments and EQ2 combat has effectively turned that portion of the game into a console video game like Nintendo of pressing the x or o button when you see the icon on the TV screen. I suppose this is arguably ok as they have eliminated KS-ing and griefing with it, but my challenge comes with the Heroic Moments themselves. 
<br />

<br />
While soloing HO’s really help you be a lot more effective. But HO’s were supposed to make group play more dramatic and fun. However, any group of more than 2 people and the success rate of HO’s drop to nearly zero. Even if people hold action while the HO wheel comes up, HO’s are typically cancelled by actions started before the HO was even pressed. Spells have long cast times. In addition, instead of actually telling the group who broke the HO like EQ1 did with mezzing, the game reports that the person who started the HO broke it which leaves a player wondering what they did wrong. I believe that HO’s in large groups is, in fact, broke but perhaps we all just need to do it differently…..
<br />

<br />
The question is…
<br />

<br />
Have you got HO’s to work? If so, how? If you do get them to work are they actually worth the cessation of action they require when they come up?</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
