			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Hello.
<br />

<br />
 We have a grp that plays together alot and have found a few different ways to get many HOs in a single fight. First is the HOs only completed by the main tank strategy. This works well for holding aggro on the MT.We have the main tank(MT) start and finsih his/hers with the taunt or similar finish to get and hold the aggro, next is the second assists(SA) turn to just hit the starter and then the MT advances it to bring up the wheel and then finishes it, next wld be any other melees turn to just start the chain, this is predetermeined b4 fighting on who is next after the MT and SA. But the main strategy here is to have the MT advance and complete all started chains. During this and any other startegies the others in the grp will only perform spells/abilities when the HO wheel is up. This doesn't break any HO because you can do anything once that wheel is up without breaking the HO oppurtunity. The other strategy we use is to take turns starting/advancing and finishing seperate HOs, first the MT will complete their own started HO to gain the aggro, then the SA will start and complete their HO without using an aggro grabbing finisher if possible, then the next in a predetermined line will start and complete theirs etc..etc..
<br />

<br />
  The thing that throws a wrench in any of these strategies is the healer not healing when the wheel is up during the battle. Now there are times that the healer must heal or someone dies, so there will be broken HOs no matter which strategy you try, but if the healer understands the HO chain and can "heal on the wheel " many HOs will not be broken. Also these 2 strategies are best used in different type encounters, a group mob that has many monsters in it such as a grp of gnolls with 3 or more in it is best dealt with the first type strategy where the MT advances and completes all HOs. If an encounter has a single group mob or just 2 mobs in it the secound strategy can be used also with a great amount of HOs being completed.
<br />

<br />
  These 2 strategies has worked very well with my group that I play with alot once we all got the kinks worked out, on a single grp mob such as a Blight Oak in Antonica we have completed up to 12 HOs in a single fight! And this has also allowed us to take on much higher lvl mobs due to our greater DPS output.So I hope this all helps everyone understand HOs in a grp setting better and how they can work if a planned strategy is followed and the healer understands to try and " heal on the wheel" if at all possible.Because once you get the strategy down the only possible breaking of HOs comes from the healer having to heal.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
